Architecture plan

Scope
- Current batch has 0 implementation issues. This session only prepares the
  repository and records the architecture for future issue-by-issue work.
- The repository is an existing static Next.js App Router site with TypeScript,
  Tailwind CSS, shared React components, static assets, and Playwright smoke
  coverage.

Module structure and file organization
- `app/` contains the App Router surface. `app/layout.tsx` owns global metadata,
  the shared shell, and document-level structure. `app/page.tsx` composes the
  homepage sections.
- `components/layout/` contains page shell components such as the header,
  footer, and content container.
- `components/sections/` contains standalone homepage sections. Section-local
  content arrays and narrow types should stay colocated with each section unless
  reused elsewhere.
- `components/ui/` contains reusable primitives such as buttons, cards, icons,
  and section wrappers. Future changes should prefer these primitives over new
  styling patterns.
- `lib/` contains shared non-UI helpers and configuration, including public
  environment handling, navigation data, and class name composition.
- `public/` contains static assets, favicon/icon files, share images, robots,
  and sitemap files required by the static export.
- `tests/e2e/` contains browser smoke tests for the statically rendered user
  experience.

Dependencies between issues
- There are no issues to implement in this setup pass.
- Future content or layout issues should generally build from shared primitives
  first, then update composed sections in `app/page.tsx`, then adjust tests.
- Future metadata, robots, sitemap, and asset issues should keep public paths
  compatible with static hosting and verify output under `out/`.
- Future behavior that touches navigation, CTA URLs, or section anchors should
  update `lib/navigation.ts`, `lib/env.ts`, and Playwright coverage together to
  avoid drift.

Key design decisions
- Keep the site fully static. Avoid server actions, route handlers, runtime
  secrets, dynamic rendering, or backend dependencies unless a future issue
  explicitly changes the product contract.
- Preserve the existing component boundaries: route composition in `app/`, page
  sections in `components/sections/`, primitives in `components/ui/`, and shared
  config/utilities in `lib/`.
- Keep homepage sections small, typed, and data-driven where that improves
  readability. Add abstractions only when they remove real duplication.
- Centralize navigation labels and anchor IDs so header, footer, sections, and
  tests remain aligned.
- Route all public CTA destination handling through `lib/env.ts` with a safe
  default for static builds.
- Validate future changes with the project tooling: `npm run format:check`,
  `npm run lint`, `npm run build`, `npm run test:e2e`, and
  `npm run verify:static` when relevant.
